segments.text: have the pleasure of being in Houston and to chat with Melvin Maltz.
Now we'll stop and hope that it's working.
This is April 28, and we're in Houston.
First question, why did you go to A&M in the first place?
What led you there instead of to somewhere else?
My dad was always interested in A&M, and he took me there.
from the time I was a little boy when he'd go up there to try to sell paper products to the dining room.
Also in 1937, 38, and 41, 42 I think.
Anyway, those three or four years I went to Camp Stewart where Bill James was then the line coach at A&M and had a great influence because he brought many of the
great stars from the 1939 and 40 football teams there for unofficial, of course, summer practices and workouts and to get in shape.
I knew many of those people and kind of felt good about following where they were because I admired them and had fun with them as a little kid.
I knew I wasn't comfortable going to co-ed school.
I had been invited to a number of co-ed schools for parties and rush parties.
I didn't like the idea of going, so I guess I just took it as help.
And I had several good friends that I grew up with that were a year ahead of me, and I thought I could get help from them if necessary and lean on them, and I ended there.
Now you grew up in Houston.
Yes.
San Jacinto High School.
San Jacinto High School, OK. And how well prepared did you think you were for college academically?
Oh, academically?
As it turned out, academically the first year wasn't bad because many or some of the subjects were repeats of what I had in high school.
But I think you might be interested in how we got the A&M the very first day.
Oh, yes.
That's the next question.
How'd you get there for that?
First beginning of instruction.
A good friend of mine that I grew up with, Gerald, Ben Broginski, now Grogan, was from Bryan.
He moved to Houston many years, or five or ten years earlier.
And we became friends, and his mother wanted to go back for a visit.
So, and the first of June was to be our high school graduation, and May 30th was thereabouts was the day we had to enroll.
So his mother drove us up there doing late, let's see, this was 1943, and she had got gasoline from somewhere.
I had a footlocker, and on the way to Gerald's house when he dropped off, I wouldn't let my parents drive us up.
I had to go to somebody else.
That was a big shock.
We stopped on the way to get my first razor and shaving brush and soap because I'd always used my father's up to then.
I didn't need it very badly, but I had to have one.
So we stopped on the way to his house, and then his parents drove us up.
Dropped me somewhere on the campus because either she couldn't, wouldn't, or I didn't want her to drive me closer.
Somehow or other, I got the footlocker up to old dorm 17.
I'm not even sure what the name of it is today.
And that was in the, quote, new dorm area?
Yes.
Describe the campus physically when you arrived.
What buildings were there and where were they?
Very dusty, very poor landscaping, walked anywhere we wanted to, no grass.
The academic building, administration building, mechanical engineering shops and building, electrical engineering building, at least what I remember those buildings to be.
Ross Hall, what they now call a trigun, I forgot what it was used for at that purpose then.
The Aggieland Inn was there.
I had been there a couple of times.
But I think that's really where I got dropped off, as a matter of fact, at the Aggieland Inn, which, as you know, was across from the Savisa Dining Hall.
Savisa was there.
Duncan was there.
Guyon Hall was there.
The old Wooden Assembly Hall was there.
Ross, Puryear, Goodwin, Law.
Guyon?
Guyon Hall, but then there's another dormitory.
I can't remember.
Right near the new area.
Individual ramps building, I can't remember.
Now, all of the new, quote, new dorm area and Duncan, they were...
Yes.
The old post office was there in the...
I guess the Sabisa lived in a similar dormitory near the mail post office.
The President's original home and another wooden building.
I forgot what it was used for then, but it turned in to be where the WordPress was, the boardroom.
That was it.
You're right.
Describe, you got there during the war, describe the student body when you arrived.
We had approximately 900 in our class.
Some of our class had started in January, I started in June, actually in the end of May, really two days or a week before I actually graduated high school.
And we had a total of about 1,900 to 2,000 total students that were various ages,
We thought the so-called sophomores and juniors were old because they were 19 and 20 years old.
Why they were still there, I don't know.
We had approximately 2,000 or so of the ASTP people there and some naval cadre, but I don't remember what they were there for or how many.
Where were those military active duty personnel living?
ASTP, at least one group that I remember was
I think it was Mitchell Hall, near Ross Hall.
In the Navy, and I think some of the others in the Navy and some of the other ASTPs had the so-called, was that the new area near Duncan, the Duncan area dormitories?
Well, what was the relationship between you Aggies and those
active duty personnel.
Well, there are several Aggies there in the ASDP people, one of which I knew from a child, as a child, from Galveston, Leon Dreyfus.
We had very little to do with them, very little anything.
The Navy V-12 participated in all kinds of student activities at the University of Texas, but the ASDP couldn't do anything except go to class in A&M.
I don't know why.
Were their classes held in the same buildings as yours?
I think there were some in the same buildings, but I don't know that we had any in our class.
I think, well, they wouldn't have had, because we were freshmen and they were juniors.
No, but there were officially freshmen, sophomores, juniors, and seniors.
Yeah, there were a few seniors, probably four out, I assume.
And was it a trimester system?
Yes.
We had three semesters, trimester system.
What was it like to be a fish then?
It really wasn't all that difficult.
And that's probably a story, too.
But of course, there wasn't supposed to be any hazing.
The first semester I was there, we had no upperclassmen living in the dormitories with us.
So the only time that we had
We formed in military units, but we had freshmen who acted as cadet officers, although they had no official rank.
So the only time we had a lot of intercourse with the upperclassmen was two in front of the mess hall.
And we got stopped occasionally on the way back from Sabisa to the dormitories because Walton was a dormitory I couldn't think of.
We had to walk in front of Walton.
And we got stopped there in discussions at various times.
Who taught y'all, who instructed you fish in Aggie traditions, lingo, et cetera?
Unfortunately, I don't think anybody did directly as far as I was concerned.
I did have some good friends.
I thought they were good friends.
There was some hazing involved.
Probably one of the two best friends I had were then sophomores, and they found uses for a broom other than sweeping floors.
All right, you mentioned such matters.
Describe what hazing, and we'll put that in quotation marks, what hazing was then.
As far as I was concerned, I'll tell it and maybe I'll ask you to take it out later.
But maybe because of the upperclassmen that I knew who were the first ones to use the broom as a weapon in a sense,
Maybe because of them, or maybe because it was me, maybe because nobody cared.
I don't know, but I really didn't have a lot of other hazing.
All right.
And this was using a broomstick?
No.
On a posterior?
It was not.
The broomstick was the handle.
The straw itself was used as the bower.
Oh, oh.
So they hit you on the rump with the broom.
Yes, with the straw of the broom.
OK.
Was this pretty well everybody?
I think so.
And how many licks would somebody get?
Well, so-called warm-up to get you accustomed to the sound and the positions and all that.
Then it was only three.
And this would happen, when it did happen, where and when?
In the corridors of Walton Hall.
And at night or day?
Mostly in after supper.
Describe a typical, as a freshman, take me through a typical weekday of drills and classes and whatever.
As far as I was concerned, thinking back, we weren't supposed to have campaign hats.
We weren't going to wear them, although the bookstore found a way to get rid of all they couldn't sell by selling them to the freshmen.
So we had them, and yet we found out later we couldn't wear them.
We also had coveralls, and we dressed in uniforms and went to class.
By what time did you get out?
I guess it was 6 o'clock.
There was reveling?
Yes.
Did you fall out and march to?
I fell out and marched to the
That's a piece of the breakfast.
We only had one small section, but because there were so few of us, probably half of the building.
I guess there was some in the small section upstairs and then some down in the basement level.
We had air raids somehow or other.
We were taught what an air raid was.
I don't know how we knew, but we knew maybe from the movie we'd never been licked.
And then we'd go back, clean up, go to class, come back for lunch.
back to dorm and then go to class again.
You were in class, classes began at 8?
8 o'clock.
We had classes five and a half days a week through noon on Saturday.
There was PE and drill of course in the afternoons and we probably got through 4 or 5 o'clock in the afternoons most days.
Saturday we had classes 8 to 12.
Right.
You fell out for the evening meal.
We had a retreat and then marched to Sevesa and then after dinner we just drifted.
Define drifting.
We'd just go to the post office, you'd go back to the dorm, some of the other classmen might meet you.
Just do nothing I guess for a while before CQ.
Then CQ was normally?
I don't remember but I guess.
7.30 maybe to 10, 7 to 10.
And lights were out at about?
About 10.
And was it unusual for somebody to go out after hours out of the dorm?
If it was, I didn't know about it.
I'm sure a lot of them did it because Northgate was so convenient.
Let's see.
I was a good boy.
I was 16 years old.
I didn't know what I was doing.
Oh, you were 16?
I was 16 in February.
Do you remember what your course load was beginning?
Well, including military science, 18, 19 hours at least.
I don't know.
It could have been 20, but I don't remember.
When you arrived, you assumed that you were going to finish your degree if you weren't called to active duty in how many years?
Two years.
I'd say two years, I guess in nine months.
And you assumed you were going to major in?
Aeronautical engineering.
Why?
Because my friend from San, well then, now from San Antonio, then from Houston was in there and I didn't know anything else to do.
I didn't have any idea what any other courses were so I just took it.
I'd also taken private flying lessons when I was in high school.
I was in, I got permission to sell my clarinet and take $50 that I sold it for and buy, I don't know, five or six hours of flying time and a Piper J-3, 65 horsepower engine.
Did you stay with that major?
Yes.
I stayed with it because when I got back I needed three semesters to graduate and anything else would have taken more.
Let's stay with dormitory and life and so forth.
You all used Aggie slang and lingo.
Help me remember some of the chow hall slang.
Oh, wow.
Gunwhiting was bread.
Grease was butter.
Blood was ketchup.
Sand was salt.
Pepper.
I don't remember what pepper was.
Tea.
Mustard.
I don't remember what tea and mustard were offhand.
Beans.
I can't think of them right now.
Let's see.
My bull neck was beef, meat, of any kind.
And dessert.
Oh, kush.
Now, did kush sometimes come through the mail?
if your mom sent you some?
I guess she sent me some.
I'm not sure I remember that.
I do remember that I kept a record of my cash expenditures and sent it home.
And to the extent that I even put, I was playing with a friend of mine at an arcade one time shooting, what do they call it?
Pinball machines.
And I put 15 cents.
and the pinball machine.
I even put that on my expenditure.
That was three cents for stamps.
Do you remember what your total expenditure was for that period?
For that particular period, it was $20, $25, I guess, for the six months, I don't know, three months, I don't know.
While we're on, do you remember what the first semester cost was?
Seemed to me like it was $125, I think, for room and board.
Maybe another $1,500 for books and stuff.
What about uniforms were provided?
Uniforms were provided, well, mostly.
I did have some extra khaki uniforms that I'd worn in the high school junior civil air patrol that I was involved in at that time.
How often did you wear civilian clothes in College Station?
Never.
Until I got to be, came back from service, I guess.
Let's see, back to meal time.
Describe some of the rituals at meal time.
Well, if there was an upperclassman at our table, which I guess didn't happen very often in the first semester, in the second semester we did have, we had to serve them first.
And if there's any shortage, we had to scrounge it from another table for them.
dessert we ate the first year, but the second semester, first semester, the second semester, if there was any left we got it.
We could eat it.

Being a good Jewish boy, I never will forget I told my mother that the food was good, but I didn't know what, I knew what roast beef was, but we had some white stuff that was, tasted like roast beef, but I didn't know what it was.
She later told me it was pork roast.
And I guess I never had it before, but I sure enjoyed it then.
All right, now, please help me on that and let me apologize in advance for mistakes of etiquette I may make.
Help me understand and help all of us understand Jewish student being at A&M at that time.
Well, there are very few of us.
My guess is, I don't know about the first
but probably in later years it got to be maybe 100 to 150.
I've always felt it was like a quarter of 1% of the student body were Jewish at that time.
We did have a Hillel organization headed first by Mrs. Esther Tottenhouse, whose husband was a professor.
Can you spell that?
T-A-U-B-E-N-H-A-U-S-E, I believe.
And he taught?
I think he, yeah.
Do you know what he taught?
No, I can't remember.
Where did those activities occur, the Hillel?
I only went once or twice, and it was somewhere, again, in the residential area at Southgate.
Southgate, okay.
And later on, Shirley Reiser, whose husband was Ray.
R-E-I-S-E-R, I think.
Took over after Mrs. Tottenhouse.
I guess she retired and got too old.
Maybe she passed away.
But except for the fact that I heard many, many years later, after I graduated, that there were some other organizations

that were on the campus, unofficial organizations, one of which I, TTs and whether it stood for lots of things, but you've probably heard it before, but the Tough Texans or maybe a few other things, to the best of my knowledge, there weren't any Jewish boys involved in that, although there could have been.
I just never know.
I wasn't.
Whether it was because of being Jewish or just nobody had interest in me, I don't know.
All right.
Was there anything that you remember that made you feel uncomfortable or was there anything done or said?
I don't ever remember anything being done or said in those years at all.
Were you all called by any kind of nickname?
No.
Fish Maltz like everybody else was.
We did not have to wear a white stripe.
They banned that because of the military.
We did not walk in the streets because they didn't want us to.
The only thing I can tell you.
And first semester, having no upperclassmen, we didn't do any details for any.
Well, that's not true.
As we were caught sometimes on the way back from dinner, we were given certain things to do.
It was very erratic.
It was sporadic.
We talked about a typical day.
Describe a typical weekend other than football season.
What did y'all, what was that like?
The first semester I guess I came home a lot.
I don't know.
I don't remember going anywhere else except on football weekends.
Thanks to Loop Hot we had various means of transportation.
Explain that, and largely.

Lou Pott, God bless him, would arrange for buses where he got, not buses, but trucks to take us to the Dallas, Fort Worth, Austin, Houston for the court trips, and we paid him some fee for going on his trucks, some of which were furniture vans with no ventilation and stuff to sit in.
Some were open with some hay, open body with hay.
I mean, I don't know.
That was probably as much hazing as ever went on, driving to and from and those things, because he mixed everybody up.
And the fee, was it low or high?
My guess, it was low, about $2 or $3 a person round trip, I suspect.
I don't remember it being anything unusual, but I'm sure he made money on it because of the numbers of people he piled on.
He also hitchhiked a lot.
In those days, that was a...
Describe Aggie hitchhiking.
Aggie hitchhiking was difficult.
He had specified places which you could start from.
Where?
Well, at the East Gate near the... What do you call the...
Granite?
That's granite.
It's...
entrance preparation as a grant.
I don't know, sandstone or something anyway.

That's where we started from going south and we started outside of the highway on Highway 6 and outside of Bryan going north and only if you were way deep in line or desperate did you take a ride in Abasota or Hearn.
Or if you're going to Huntsville, out of Bryan, would you go to anywhere but non-stop to Huntsville?
And when you're hitchhiking to Houston, normally how long would it take to get a ride to Houston?
It didn't seem like it'd take very long.
And it seemed like there were a lot of people going back and forth.
Of course, we always had to introduce ourselves.
We weren't supposed to go to sleep.
And I'll tell you a quick sideline to that.
On the way to LSU, Baton Rouge for a football game, my then roommate, and I guess we were sophomores at the time, we took a ride to Lake Charles, which we weren't supposed to do.
And it got raining.
It was raining.
And so we went inside the Edelwein, and it was nighttime.
We had gotten a ride to Houston.
My mother and dad took us to the outside highway to go to, let's see, it was Highway 90 out of Houston.
And we started there with them.
And we got a ride late.
It was maybe 7, 8 o'clock, 9, whatever it was at night.
But we got to Lake Charles.
We went in, had something to eat and a drink.
And I guess we were maybe 17.
We sat there for a while and put a stop light and went back out the highway to get a ride to Baton Rouge.
We get a ride, and the man has his heater on.
Of course, coming out of a hot building and damp, cold, and having had a drink, we got sleepy and weren't supposed to, and we fell asleep.
And he asked us afterwards,
We weren't supposed to stay awake.
We said, yes.
He said, you weren't supposed to drink either, were you?
I said, drink?
He introduced himself as a minister from some congregation.
That story, I don't think he'll forget.
Do you remember any negative hitchhiking?
Oh, yes.
One night we hitched, one day weekend, a friend of mine, we hitchhiked to Huntsville.
For some reason, the girls didn't want to go out with us.
So we had something to eat and went back from Huntsville.
We took a ride to Madisonville and then trying to get over to College Station.
And we got there and we thought it was the last picture show in town.
Nobody was going to college, to Bryant.
We couldn't get a ride.
We stayed out until 2 or 3 o'clock in the morning.
And finally ended up going to sleep on a bench in a hotel there until about 6 the next morning.
Then we got a ride on a gasoline truck.
and managed to get there the next day.
We didn't get home very quickly.
All right, did you or any of your friends ever have anything
unfortunate happened to you much on that trip?
Not as I recall.
I haven't heard any bad stories.
I haven't gotten a single one yet.
I've never heard a negative story.
Being in uniform was always, at that time anyway, everybody was willing to help.
Even those who didn't recognize A&M uniforms.
And I gather that you, that nobody held up a sign that said Houston or Dallas.
No, we always used a phone.
That you put up.
I don't know that we didn't have a sign at some point out there.
Particularly, I guess, if we were going to Baton Rouge, which we probably did.
But I don't think it was ever necessary going to Houston or Dallas.
Tell me about your outfit, your core outfit.
Well, the first semester was all freshmen.
We had... Did it have a name and a nickname?
Not at that time, no.
The first semester was Darm 17.
I don't think we had a guide on even that I recall.
But they were all freshmen.
They just took some people with high school ROTC experiences, so-called cadet officers.
As far as you know, was that true for all of the undergraduate student body?
In that summer of 1943, yes.
Well, all the freshmen.
When the fall began.
When the fall began, then they moved some sophomores and juniors in with us.
And what were you all called then, or do you know?
This company, as I recall, I don't remember.
What you're then, I hadn't thought about this, what you're alerting me to is that in the middle of the war, some of the core unit traditions were kind of gone.
They were gone because we didn't have any designation, no milito brass that we wore designated
I think we could wear anything we wanted to.
I don't remember.
So you weren't then identified as Field Artillery, Signal Corps, Infantry?
Was there a Corps Commander?
Yes.
Okay, so that continued.
Yeah, I can show you probably the Cook Hall Longhorn when we get to the house tonight.
Maybe we can look some of that up.
Let's see.
Tell me about some of your special, special friends from those early years.
Dwayne Bennett has remained a friend.
And I saw him even overseas while we were in service.
We ran into each other at the muster in 1946.
L.M.
Gabert was from Houston.
And of course, I saw him often there as well as at the same muster in 1946.
That's a good story, too.
Go ahead.
Who else?
Special friends was, as far as freshmen were concerned, Frank Looney was my roommate.
He had a date for our freshman ball.
I didn't have a date.
I went out and we bought some whiskey, which we weren't supposed to have, and I forgot who I was with.
But I know I must have had at least two drinks, but probably that's all it took, and I got just sick.
But not until I got in the upper bunk, and not until I had...
I eventually gave it up into his shoes, and he came in sometime later that night and didn't stay, and came back the next morning and said, it's your problem, you clean them up.
Which, of course, I did.
Also, the first day I was on the campus, we went across the hall to a room with Dwayne Bennett
Why would a guy end up in a paratrooper's anyway?
There must have been more than how many people in there.
Everybody's smoking and I didn't smoke.
But of course I had to try one during I got sick then also and I didn't smoke a cent.
Alright, share with me if you will some of the jokes, pranks, good bull of your student days.
involving you or anyone else?
RM-17 was known as SS-17 in our first semester.
SS?
Yeah.
We were a steamship because there was so much, I mean, drowned outs going on and so many people turned on the fire extinguishers which were on the fourth floor, flooded the building.
We thought it was, we thought it was going to float away.
I didn't have a little, I had a first lieutenant in the cavalry who was our
What did we call him?
Not a military officer.
Anyway, he was the officer in charge of our dorm and he got his boots soaked one time and didn't like it at all.
Jock Burns was his, we called him.
His name was Lieutenant Burns is all I recall.
As far as the other... How did, how was a drowned out done?
How did y'all do that?
He had a bucket of water and he'd run in quick and block his door so he couldn't get out.
with a broomstick or he'd lean one against his door so that if he opened it, it would float.
I guess that was it.
It never happened to me.
And again, I don't know whether that was the reason.
This never happened.
